"encrypted":true,"parser":null,"secureConnecting":false,"servername":"api.deepseek.com","ssl":{"_parent":{"onconnection":null,"reading":true},"_parentWrap":null,"_secureContext":{"context":{}},"reading":true},"timeout":5000},"complete":true,"httpVersion":"1.1","httpVersionMajor":1,"httpVersionMinor":1,"method":null,"rawHeaders":["Content-Type","application/json","Content-Length","111","Connection","keep-alive","Date","Wed, 11 Mar 2026 17:12:37 GMT","Server","elb","vary","origin, access-control-request-method, access-control-request-headers","access-control-allow-credentials","true","x-ds-trace-id","976ff4490a1ed348cfb13872b19105d5","Strict-Transport-Security","max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload","X-Content-Type-Options","nosniff","X-Cache","Error from cloudfront","Via","1.1 7934810974a311f6bc8a88cb98e8c0a6.cloudfront.net (CloudFront)","X-Amz-Cf-Pop","MRS52-P3","X-Amz-Cf-Id","wOB_pGCUqpAVGOlThLdRlEuAfsIk7bY91kdBGD3Y4SVoJLKMJPH-Cw=="],"rawTrailers":[],"redirects":[],"req":"[Circular]","responseUrl":"https://api.deepseek.com/v1/chat/completions","socket":null,"statusCode":402,"statusMessage":"Payment Required","upgrade":false,"url":""},"reusedSocket":false,"sendDate":false,"shouldKeepAlive":true,"strictContentLength":false,"timeoutCb":null,"upgradeOrConnect":false,"useChunkedEncodingByDefault":true,"writable":true},"response":{"config":{"adapter":["xhr","http","fetch"],"allowAbsoluteUrls":true,"data":"{\"model\":\"deepseek-chat\",\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"system\",\"content\":\"You are a helpful assistant that summarizes documents. \\n              Return a JSON object with exactly this structure:\\n              {\\n                \\\"brief\\\": \\\"string (2-3 sentences)\\\",\\n                \\\"mainPoints\\\": [\\\"string\\\", \\\"string\\\", ...] (3-5 bullet points),\\n                \\\"keyPhrases\\\": [\\\"string\\\", \\\"string\\\", ...] (5-10 key terms)\\n              }\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Please summarize the following document.\\n\\nProvide a brief overview, 3-5 main points, and 5-10 key phrases.\\n\\nDocument:\\nChapter 4.\\nInheritance\\nINSTRUCTOR: DR. ABED EL SAFADI\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nREFERENCES\\nThe content of this presentation is prepared based on:\\noABSOLUTE JAVA \\t6th Edition Global Edition\\noPowerPoint Lecture Slides for Absolute Java, Global Edition\\noWebsites notes\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t2\\nPart 1 •Introduction to Inheritance\\n•Overriding a Method Definition\\n•The \\tsuper \\tconstructor\\n•The \\tthis \\tconstructor\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t3\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nShared Functionality – Code Duplication\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t4\\npublic class Student {\\nString fullName;\\nString gender;\\nint dayOfBirth;\\nString monthOfBirth;\\nint yearOfBirth;\\nint id;\\ndouble gpa;\\nString major;\\nString universityName = “LU”;\\ndouble getGpa() { … }\\n…………..\\nString getFullName() { … }\\n…………..\\n}\\npublic class Teacher {\\nString fullName;\\nString gender;\\nint dayOfBirth;\\nString monthOfBirth;\\nint yearOfBirth;\\nint papers;\\ndouble salary;\\nint getPapers() { … }\\n…………..\\nString getFullName() { … }\\n…………..\\n}\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\npublic class Person {\\nString fullName;\\nString gender;\\nint dayOfBirth;\\nString monthOfBirth;\\nint yearOfBirth;\\nString getFullName() { … }\\n…………..\\n}\\npublic class Student \\textends \\tPerson{\\nint id;\\ndouble gpa;\\nString major;\\nString universityName = “LU”;\\ndouble getGpa() { … }\\n…………..\\n}\\npublic class Teacher \\textends \\tPerson {\\nint papers;\\ndouble salary;\\nint getPapers() { … }\\n…………..\\n}\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t5\\nShared Functionality – Solution\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nSo… What is Inheritance? \\t(1/3)\\nIt is one of the main techniques of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)\\nIt represents the “is-a” relationship\\nIt is the process by which:\\noA new class is created from another class (original class): a very general form of a\\nclass is first defined and compiled, and then more specialized versions of the class\\nare defined \\tby adding instance variables and methods\\nThe original class is called the \\tbase \\tclass, \\tparent \\tclass, \\tancestor, or \\tsuperclass\\nThe new class is called a \\tderived \\tclass, \\tchild \\tclass, \\tdescendent of, \\tor \\tsubclass\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t6\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nSo… What is Inheritance? \\t(2/3)\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t7\\nbase, parent, ancestor, superclass\\nderived, child, \\tdescendent of, \\tsubclass\\nderived, child, \\tdescendent of, \\tsubclass\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThe derived class is said to inherit from the parent class:\\noInstance variables\\noStatic/final variables\\noMethods\\nIn addition, the derived class can:\\noHave additional instance variables\\noHave additional methods\\noOverride inherited methods\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t8\\nSo… What is Inheritance? \\t(3/3)\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nAdvantages of Inheritance\\nWhen you use inheritance to create the \\tStudent \\tand \\tTeacher \\tclasses, you make the\\ncode of the class \\tPerson \\tmore easily reusable. Thus, you:\\noSave time to create the \\tStudent \\tand \\tTeacher \\tclasses because the \\tPerson \\tfields and\\nmethods already exist\\noReduce errors because the \\tPerson \\tmethods already have been used and tested\\noReduce the amount of new learning required for programmers to use the new\\nclasses if they are already familiar with the original class\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t9\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nCreating a Derived Class - Syntax\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t10\\npublic class \\tStudent \\textends \\tPerson{\\nint grade;\\nint getGrade() {\\n…\\n}\\n}\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nClass Hierarchy\\nEach Java class has one (and only one) superclass\\nInheritance creates a class hierarchy\\no \\tClasses higher in the hierarchy are more general and\\nmore abstract\\no \\tClasses lower in the hierarchy are more specific and\\nconcrete\\nThere is no limit to the number of subclasses a class\\ncan have\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t11\\nClass A\\nClass B \\tClass C \\tClass D\\nClass H\\nClass E \\tClass G\\tClass F\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t12\\nClass Hierarchy - Example\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThink of it like an onion…\\nIf class \\tGraduateStudent \\textends class \\tStudent, which extends class \\tPerson, then, an\\nobject of class \\tGraduateStudent \\twill have the members of \\tStudent \\tand \\tPerson\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t13\\nGraduateStudent \\tand its members\\nStudent \\tand its members\\nPerson \\tand its members\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t14\\nInheritance\\nDiagrams\\nInheritance \\tdiagrams \\tare \\tused \\tto\\nindicate \\thow \\tobjects \\tof \\tthe \\tvarious\\nclasses interact with each others\\nStudent\\n- \\tid: \\tint\\n- \\tgpa: \\tdouble\\n- \\tmajor: \\tString\\n- \\tuniversityName: \\tString\\n+ \\tconstructors\\n+ \\tgetters\\n+ \\tsetters\\n+ \\ttoString(): String\\nPerson\\n- \\tfullName: \\tString\\n- \\tgender: \\tString\\n- \\tdayOfBirth: \\tint\\n- \\tmonthOfBirth: \\tString\\n- \\tyearOfBirth: \\tint\\n+ \\tconstructors\\n+ \\tgetters\\n+ \\tsetters\\n+ \\ttoString(): String\\nTeacher\\n- \\tpapers: \\tint\\n- \\tsalary: \\tdouble\\n+ \\tconstructors\\n+ \\tgetters\\n+ \\tsetters\\n+ \\ttoString(): String\\nPart 1 •Introduction to Inheritance\\n•Overriding a Method Definition\\n•The \\tsuper \\tconstructor\\n•The \\tthis \\tconstructor\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t15\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nOverriding a Method Definition\\nAlthough a derived class inherits methods from the base class, it can override an\\ninherited method if necessary\\nMethod overriding \\tis a case in which the subclass and superclass contain methods that\\nhave the \\tsame name and signature\\nTo override a method definition, a new definition of the method is placed in the class\\ndefinition, just like any other method that is added to the derived class\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t16\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nAs a general rule, when overriding a method definition, \\tyou may not:\\noChange the type returned by the method\\noChange a void method to a method that returns a value\\noChange a method that returns a value to a void method\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t17\\nOverriding a Method Definition\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nOverriding a Method Definition\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t18\\nWhen a subclass overrides (redefines) the\\nmethods of the superclass\\no \\tObjects of the subclass type will use\\nthe new method\\no \\tObjects of the superclass type will use\\nthe original method\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nOverriding the Method \\ttoString()\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t19\\npublic class \\tPerson{\\npublic String toString() {\\nreturn “The full name is: “ +fullName + “, the gender is: “ + gender;\\n}\\n}\\npublic class \\tStudent \\textends \\tPerson{\\npublic String toString() {\\nreturn “The id is: “ +id + “, the gpa is: “ + gpa + “, the major is: ” + major;\\n}\\n}\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nAccess Permission of an Overridden Method\\nYou can’t change the access permission of an overridden method from public in the\\nbase class to private in the derived class (or in any other way that makes access\\npermissions less permissive)\\nGiven the following method header in a base case:\\npublic void doSomething()\\nThe following method header \\tis not valid \\tin a derived class:\\nprivate void doSomething()\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t20\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nCalling methods of the superclass\\nIf a subclass does not override public methods of a superclass, specify call to public\\nmethods of the superclass as follows:\\nMethodName(parameters list);\\nIf a subclass overrides public methods of a superclass, specify call to public methods of\\nthe superclass as follows:\\nsuper.MethodName(parameters list);\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t21\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nCalling methods of the superclass - Syntax\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t22\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nOverriding the Method \\ttoString()\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t23\\npublic class \\tPerson{\\npublic String toString() {\\nreturn “The full name is: “ +fullName+ “, the gender is: “ + gender; }\\n}\\npublic class \\tStudent \\textends \\tPerson{\\npublic String toString() {\\nreturn “The full name is: “ + getFullName() + “, the gender is: “ + getGender()\\n+ “, the id is: “ +id + “, the gpa is: “ + gpa + “, the major is: ” + major; }\\n}\\npublic class \\tStudent \\textends \\tPerson{\\npublic String toString() {\\nreturn super.toString() + “, the id is: “ +id + “, the gpa is: “ + gpa + “, the major is: ” + major; }\\n}\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nAnother example: \\tClass \\tRectangle\\nWhat if we want to implement a 3d box object?\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t24\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nClass \\tBox\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t25\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nObjects \\tmyRectangle \\tand \\tmyBox\\nRectangle myRectangle = new Rectangle(5, 3);\\nBox myBox = new Box(6, 5, 4);\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t26\\nBoth a Rectangle and a Box\\nhave a surface area,\\nbut they are computed\\ndifferently\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nclass \\tRectangle{\\npublic double \\tarea() {\\nreturn \\tgetLength() * getWidth();\\n}\\n}\\nclass \\tBox{\\npublic double \\tarea() {\\nreturn \\t2 * (getLength() * getWidth()\\n+ getLength() * height\\n+ getWidth() * height);\\n}\\n}\\nOverriding the Method \\tarea()\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t27\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nclass \\tRectangle{\\npublic double \\tarea() {\\nreturn \\tgetLength() * getWidth();\\n}\\n}\\nclass \\tBox{\\npublic double \\tarea() {\\nreturn \\t2 * (getLength() * getWidth() + getLength() * height +\\ngetWidth() * height);\\n}\\n}\\nOverriding the Method \\tarea()\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t28\\nclass \\tBox{\\npublic double \\tarea() {\\nreturn \\t2 * (super.area() + getLength() * height + getWidth() * height);\\n}\\n}\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThe \\tfinal \\tModifier with Methods\\nIf the modifier \\tfinal \\tis placed before the definition of a method, then, that method may\\nnot be redefined (overrided) in a derived class\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t29\\nclass B extends A{\\n@Override\\npublic \\tfinal \\tvoid doSomeThing() { \\t... \\t}\\n}\\nclass A{\\npublic \\tfinal \\tvoid doSomeThing() { ... }\\n}\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThe \\tfinal \\tModifier with Classes\\nIf the modifier \\tfinal \\tis placed before the definition of a class, then, that class may not\\nbe used as a base class to derive other classes\\npublic \\tfinal \\tclass A { … }\\npublic \\tclass B extends A { … }\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t30\\nPart 1 •Introduction to Inheritance\\n•Overriding a Method Definition\\n•The \\tsuper \\tconstructor\\n•The \\tthis \\tconstructor\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t31\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThe \\tsuper \\tConstructor\\nWhen instantiating a subclass object, two constructors are actually called:\\n1. \\tThe constructor for the base class: it is used initialize all the data inherited from\\nthe base class\\n2. \\tThe constructor for the extended (derived) class\\nA call to the superclass constructor can never use the name of the base class, but uses\\nthe keyword \\tsuper \\tinstead\\nA call to \\tsuper \\tmust always be the first action taken in a constructor definition: when\\nyou create any subclass object, the superclass constructor must execute first, and then,\\nthe subclass constructor executes\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t32\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThe \\tsuper \\tConstructor - Example\\nA constructor for a derived class invokes a constructor from the base class in a special\\nway\\nIn the above example, \\tsuper(fullName); \\tis a call to the base class constructor\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t33\\npublic class Person {\\nPerson(String fullName){\\nthis.fullName = fullName;\\n}\\n}\\npublic class Student extends Person {\\nStudent(String fullName, double major) {\\nsuper(fullName);\\nthis.major = major;\\n}\\n}\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThe \\tsuper \\tConstructor\\nThe constructor of the subclass always calls a constructor of the superclass, explicitly or\\nimplicitly\\nIf a derived class constructor does not include an explicit invocation of \\tsuper, then the\\nno-argument constructor of the base class will automatically be invoked\\noThis can result in an error if the base class has not defined a no-argument constructor\\nWe can use \\tsuper() \\tonly inside constructor and nowhere else, not even inside methods\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t34\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThe \\tsuper \\t& \\tthis \\tConstructors\\nA constructor definition cannot contain both an invocation of \\tsuper \\tand an invocation\\nof \\tthis\\nWe can use \\tsuper \\tas well \\tthis \\tonly once inside constructor\\nIf we use \\tsuper \\ttwice or \\tthis \\ttwice or \\tsuper \\tfollowed by \\tthis \\tor \\tthis \\tfollowed by\\nsuper, \\tthen immediately we get compile time error\\nIt is up to you that whether you use \\tsuper \\tor \\tthis \\tor not because if we are not using\\nthis \\tor \\tsuper \\tthen by default compiler will put \\tsuper \\tas first statement inside the\\nconstructor of the derived class\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t35\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t36\\nThe \\tsuper \\t& \\tthis\\nConstructors -\\nExample\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nRecursive constructor\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t37\\npublic class A {\\nA(){\\nthis(30);\\n}\\nA(int a){\\nthis();\\n}\\npublic static void main(){\\nnew A();\\n}\\n}\\nPart 2 •Encapsulation and Inheritance\\n• \\tAccessibility Levels, Protected and Package Access\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t38\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nAccessibility Levels\\npublic \\tmembers \\tare \\tinherited: \\tthe \\tsubclass \\t“sees” \\tthe \\tpublic \\tmembers \\tof \\tthe\\nsuperclass\\nprivate \\tmembers are inherited but not accessible / hidden: to access/modify the\\nprivate members of the superclass in the subclass, we have to use the getters/setters\\nprotected \\tmembers are inherited: the subclass “sees” the protected members of the\\nsuperclass; for the other classes, protected members act as private members\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t39\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nprivate \\tAccess\\nAn instance variable or method that is \\tprivate \\tin a base class is not accessible by name\\nin the definition of a method in any other class, not even in a method definition of a\\nderived class\\nIn the definition of a derived class, you cannot mention a \\tprivate \\tinherited instance\\nvariable by name\\n• \\tYou must instead use \\tpublic \\taccessors and mutators that were defined in the base\\nclass\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t40\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nprotected \\tAccess\\nprotected \\taccess provides an intermediate level of security between \\tpublic \\tand \\tprivate\\naccess\\nIf a method or instance variable is modified by \\tprotected, \\tit can be accessed by name:\\n• \\tInside its own class definition\\n• \\tInside any class derived from it\\n• \\tIn the definition of any class in the same package (even if the class in the same\\npackage is not derived from it)\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t41\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\n“None”(package) Access\\nIf you forget to place one of the modifiers \\tpublic, \\tprivate, or \\tprotected \\tbefore an\\ninstance variable or method definition, then your class definition will still compile\\nIf you do not place any of these modifiers before an instance variable or method\\ndefinition, then the instance variable or method can be accessed by name:\\n• \\tInside its own class definition\\n• \\tInside the definition of any class in the same package\\n• \\tBut not outside of the package\\nThis is called package access, default access, or friendly access\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t42\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nAccess Modifiers - \\tSummary\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t43\\nDifferent\\npackage\\nSubclass\\tSame package\\tSame class\\tModifier\\nY\\tY\\tY\\tY\\tpublic\\nN\\tY\\tY\\tY\\tprotected\\nN\\tN\\tN\\tY\\tprivate\\nN\\tN\\tY\\tY\\t“package”\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t44\\nAccess Modifiers -\\nSummary\\nPart 3 •Programming with Inheritance\\n• \\tThe Class \\tObject\\n• \\tStatic Members\\n• \\tComposition Relationship\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t45\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThe Class \\tObject \\t(1/2)\\nIn Java, every class is a descendent of the class \\tObject\\n• \\tEvery class has \\tObject \\tas its ancestor\\n• \\tEvery object of every class is of type \\tObject, as well as being of the type of its own\\nclass\\n• \\tIf a class is defined that is not explicitly a derived class of another class, it is still\\nautomatically a derived class of the class \\tObject\\nCHAPTER 4 - INHERITANCE \\t46\\nDr. Abed EL Safadi\\nThe Class \\tObject \\t(2/2)\\nThe class \\tObject \\tis in the package \\tjava.\"}],\"temperature\":0.3,\"max_tokens\":1000,\"response_format\":{\"type\":\"json_object\"}}","env":{},"headers":{"Accept":"application/json, text/plain, */*","Accept-Encoding":"gzip, compress, deflate, br","Authorization":"Bearer sk-e6c25806e5b7447e98a4ec0199a93bc0","Content-Length":"16711","Content-Type":"application/json","User-Agent":"axios/1.13.4"},"maxBodyLength":-1,"maxContentLength":-1,"method":"post","timeout":0,"transformRequest":[null],"transformResponse":[null],"transitional":{"clarifyTimeoutError":false,"forcedJSONParsing":true,"silentJSONParsing":true},"url":"https://api.deepseek.com/v1/chat/completions","xsrfCookieName":"XSRF-TOKEN","xsrfHeaderName":"X-XSRF-TOKEN"},"data":{"error":{"code":"invalid_request_error","message":"Insufficient Balance","param":null,"type":"unknown_error"}},"headers":{"access-control-allow-credentials":"true","connection":"keep-alive","content-length":"111","content-type":"application/json","date":"Wed, 11 Mar 2026 17:12:37 GMT","server":"elb","strict-transport-security":"max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload","vary":"origin, access-control-request-method, access-control-request-headers","via":"1.1 7934810974a311f6bc8a88cb98e8c0a6.cloudfront.net (CloudFront)","x-amz-cf-id":"wOB_pGCUqpAVGOlThLdRlEuAfsIk7bY91kdBGD3Y4SVoJLK