{"code":"ERR_BAD_REQUEST","config":{"adapter":["xhr","http","fetch"],"allowAbsoluteUrls":true,"data":"{\"model\":\"deepseek-chat\",\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"system\",\"content\":\"You are a helpful assistant that summarizes documents. \\n              Return a JSON object with exactly this structure:\\n              {\\n                \\\"brief\\\": \\\"string (2-3 sentences)\\\",\\n                \\\"mainPoints\\\": [\\\"string\\\", \\\"string\\\", ...] (3-5 bullet points),\\n                \\\"keyPhrases\\\": [\\\"string\\\", \\\"string\\\", ...] (5-10 key terms)\\n              }\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Please summarize the following document.\\n\\nProvide a brief overview, 3-5 main points, and 5-10 key phrases.\\n\\nDocument:\\nI3344\\nNumerical Simulation & Modelling\\nAhmad Fadlallah\\nLebanese University / Faculty of Science - I\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Numerical Simulation & Modelling 1 / 60\\nInterpolation and Extrapolation\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 2 / 60\\nGeneral Introduction\\nGeneral Introduction\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 3 / 60\\nGeneral Introduction\\nGeneral Introduction\\nSuppose that you have plotted a number of data points on a coordinate\\nplane, with the x-coordinate of each data point representing the number\\nof months since you have planted a tree, and the y-coordinate of each\\npoint representing the tree’s height in meters.\\nIf you have data for 1 month, 2 months, 3 months, and 4 months:\\n\\u0004 Do you think you could guess what the tree’s height will be at 5\\nmonths?\\n\\u0004 How about what the tree’s height was at 2.5 months?\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 4 / 60\\nGeneral Introduction\\nGeneral Introduction (cont’d)\\n\\u0004 In many cases, we know the values of a function f (x) at a set of\\npoints x1 < x2 < ... < xN , but we don’t have the analytic expression\\nof the function that lets us calculate its value at an arbitrary\\npoint.\\n\\u0004 We will try to estimate f (x) for arbitrary x by ”drawing” a curve\\nthrough the xi and sometimes beyond them.\\n\\u0004 Usually known as ”Curve Fitting”\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 5 / 60\\nGeneral Introduction\\nGeneral Introduction (cont’d)\\nBUT why do we need such things?\\n\\u0004 Simulation\\n\\u0004 Computer Graphics\\n\\u0004 Modeling/ Forecast\\n\\u0004 Artificial Intelligence\\n\\u0004 Machine Learning\\n\\u0004 Several research and application domains\\n\\u0004 etc.\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 6 / 60\\nGeneral Introduction\\nGeneral Introduction (cont’d)\\nThe procedure of estimating the value of f(x) is called:\\n\\u0004 Interpolation for x ∈[x1, xN ]\\n\\u0004 Extrapolation for x /∈ [x1,xN ]\\nThe form of the function that approximates the set of points should be a\\nconvenient one.\\nDifferent estimation methods are available\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 7 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nLinear Regression\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 8 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nIntroduction\\nPolynomial approximation is usually used to find a polynomial function\\nof order n (for n points) :\\nf (x) = an−1xn−1 + ... + a0\\n\\u0004 Finding coefficients ai requires resolving a system of n equations in n\\nunknowns\\n\\u0004 Different methods were proposed for polynomial approximations\\nI Lagrange’s Polynomial\\nI Hermite Polynomial\\nI Taylor Polynomial\\nI Cubic Splines\\nI etc.\\n\\u0004 The resulting curve will pass through all the n points\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 9 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nIntroduction (cont’d)\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 10 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nIntroduction (cont’d)\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 11 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nIntroduction (cont’d)\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 12 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nIntroduction (cont’d)\\n\\u0004 When data exhibit a significant degree of error or “noise”, the\\nstrategy is to derive a single curve that represents the general trend\\nof these data.\\n\\u0004 Because any individual data point may be incorrect, no effort is made\\nto intersect every point.\\n\\u0004 The curve is designed to follow the pattern of the points taken as\\na group.\\n\\u0004 One approach of this nature is called Least-Squares Regression\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 13 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nIntroduction (cont’d)\\nData Polynomial Fit Least-Square Fit\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 14 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nLinear Regression - Definition\\n\\u0004 Simplest example of a least-squares approximation is fitting a\\nstraight line to a set of paired observations:\\n(x1, y1), (x2, y2), ..., (xn, yn)\\n\\u0004 The mathematical expression for the straight line is:\\ny = a0 + a1x + e\\nI a0 and a1 are coefficients representing the intercept and the slope\\nrespectively\\nI e is the error, or residual, between the model and the observations\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 15 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nLinear Regression - Definition (cont’d)\\nThe error (e) can be represented by rearranging the equation as:\\ne = y − a0 − a1x = y − (a0 + a1x) = y − ˆy\\nThe error (e) is the discrepancy between the true value of y and the ap-\\nproximate value ˆy by the linear equation\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 16 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nCriteria for a Best Fit\\nFirst Approach:\\nMinimize the sum of residual errors\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\nei =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − a0 − a1xi )\\nwhere n is the total number of points\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 17 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nCriteria for a Best Fit\\nFirst Approach:\\nMinimize the sum of residual errors\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\nei =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − a0 − a1xi )\\nwhere n is the total number of points\\nNOT A Good Choice\\nsince the errors might cancel\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 17 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nCriteria for a Best Fit (cont’d)\\nSecond Approach:\\nMinimize the sum of absolute values of residual errors\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n|ei | =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n|(yi − a0 − a1xi )|\\nwhere n is the total number of points\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 18 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nCriteria for a Best Fit (cont’d)\\nSecond Approach:\\nMinimize the sum of absolute values of residual errors\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n|ei | =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n|(yi − a0 − a1xi )|\\nwhere n is the total number of points\\nNOT A Good Choice\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 18 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nCriteria for a Best Fit (cont’d)\\nThird Approach:\\nMinimize the Sum of Squares of residual Errors (SSE) or Sr\\nSr =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n|e2\\ni | =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − ˆy )2 =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − a0 − a1xi )2\\nwhere n is the total number of points\\nThis approach allows to overcome the shortcomings of the previous ap-\\nproaches\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 19 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nLeast-Squares Fit of a Straight Line\\nSr =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n|e2\\ni | =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − ˆy )2 =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − a0 − a1xi )2\\nDifferentiate the equation with respect to each coefficient a0 and a1\\nδSr\\nδa0\\n= −2 ∑\\ni\\n(yi − a0 − a1xi )\\nδSr\\nδa1\\n= −2 ∑\\ni\\n[(yi − a0 − a1xi )xi ]\\nMinimize Sr ⇒ δSr\\nδa0\\n= δSr\\nδa1\\n= 0\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 20 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nLeast-Squares Fit of a Straight Line (cont’d)\\n0 = ∑ (yi − a0 − a1xi ) = ∑ yi − ∑ a0 − ∑ a1xi\\n0 = ∑ [(yi − a0 − a1xi )xi ] = ∑ yi xi − ∑ a0xi − ∑ a1x2\\ni\\n∑ a0 = na0\\nna0 + (∑ xi )a1 = ∑ yi\\n(∑ xi )a0 + (∑ x2\\ni )a1 = ∑ xi yi\\na1 = n(∑ xi yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2 , a0 = (∑ xi )2(∑ yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ xi yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 21 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nLeast-Squares Fit of a Straight Line (cont’d)\\nSummary\\na1 = n(∑ xi yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2\\na0 = y − a1x\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 22 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nExercise\\nFit a straight line to the following x and y values\\nxi yi\\n1 0.5\\n2 2.5\\n3 2.0\\n4 4.0\\n5 3.5\\n6 6.0\\n7 5.5\\na1 = n(∑ xi yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2\\na0 = y − a1x\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 23 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nExercise\\nFit a straight line to the following x and y values\\nxi yi\\n0.2 8.2\\n0.4 8.4\\n0.6 8.5\\n0.8 8.6\\n1.0 8.8\\n1.2 8.7\\na1 = n(∑ xi yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2\\na0 = y − a1x\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 24 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nBackground - Statistics\\nConsider a set of n values y1, ..., yn\\n\\u0004 Mean: y =\\n∑ yi\\nn\\n\\u0004 Standard Deviation : allows to express the dispersion of the values\\naround their mean i.e. the average distance between the values and\\ntheir mean.\\nσ = √ν where the variance ν = [∑n\\ni=1 (xi − ¯x)2]\\nn\\n\\u0004 Correlation: Describe the relation between two variables\\nr = cor (x, y ) = cov (x, y )\\n(σx ∗ σy )\\ncov (x, y ) =\\n∑n\\ni=1 (xi − ¯x)(yi − ¯y )\\nn\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 25 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nBackground - Statistics\\nThe correlation coefficient r ∈ [-1, 1] in contrast to the covariance that is\\ninfluenced by the range of values of x and y .\\nThree types of correlation:\\n\\u0004 Positive correlation: x ↗ ⇒ y ↗\\n\\u0004 Negative correlation: x ↗ ⇒ y ↘\\n\\u0004 Zero correlation: No relationship exists between x and y.\\nThe closer the value is to 1 or -1, the stronger the link.\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 26 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nLinear Regression - Revisited\\na1 = n(∑ xi yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2 , a0 = (∑ xi )2(∑ yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ xi yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2\\na1 = r ∗ σy\\nσx\\n, a0 = ¯y − a1 ¯x\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 27 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nLinear Regression - Revisited\\na1 = n(∑ xi yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2 , a0 = (∑ xi )2(∑ yi ) − (∑ xi )(∑ xi yi )\\nn(∑ x2\\ni ) − (∑ xi )2\\na1 = r ∗ σy\\nσx\\n, a0 = ¯y − a1 ¯x\\nExercise: Prove a1 = r ∗ σy\\nσx\\nσ = √ν, ν = [∑n\\ni=1 (xi − ¯x)2]\\nn\\nr = cor (x, y ) = cov (x, y )\\n(σx ∗ σy )\\ncov (x, y ) =\\n∑n\\ni=1 (xi − ¯x)(yi − ¯y )\\nn\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 27 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nQuantification of Error of Linear Regression\\n\\u0004 Any line other than the one computed results in a larger Sum of the\\nSquares of the Residuals (SSE)\\n\\u0004 The line is unique and in terms of our chosen criterion is a ”best”\\nline through the points.\\n\\u0004 How to calculate error in Linear Regression?\\nSuggestion: Using the Sum of the Squares of the Residuals (SSE)\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 28 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nExercise\\nUsing previously calculated coefficients, calculate the SSE\\nxi yi\\n1 0.5\\n2 2.5\\n3 2.0\\n4 4.0\\n5 3.5\\n6 6.0\\n7 5.5\\nSr = SSE =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n|e2\\ni | =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − ˆy )2 =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − a0 − a1xi )2\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 29 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nQuantification of Error of Linear Regression\\nHow to evaluate the accuracy of a1 and a0?\\n\\u0004 The value of SSE does not make it possible to evaluate the accuracy\\nof these two coefficients.\\n\\u0004 Example: an error of 2.5 on a set of data belonging to the interval\\n[1000, 1500] is negligible in comparison with the same value on\\nanother set belonging to the interval [0,1].\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 30 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nQuantification of Error of Linear Regression\\nHow to evaluate the accuracy of a1 and a0?\\n\\u0004 The value of SSE does not make it possible to evaluate the accuracy\\nof these two coefficients.\\n\\u0004 Example: an error of 2.5 on a set of data belonging to the interval\\n[1000, 1500] is negligible in comparison with the same value on\\nanother set belonging to the interval [0,1].\\nSolution: Normalize the Error\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 30 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nQuantification of Error of Linear Regression (cont’d)\\nMethod 1: Use Normalized Root-Mean-Square Error (NRMSE)\\nMSE = SSE\\nn , RMSE =\\n√\\nSSE\\nn , NRMSE = RMSE\\n¯y\\n\\u0004 NRMSE close to 0 ⇒ Perfect model\\n\\u0004 NRMSE close to 1 ⇒ Null model\\nNRMSE might be expressed as follows:\\nNRMSE = RMSE\\n(Max − Min)\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 31 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nExercise\\nCalculate the NRMSE and Evaluate\\nxi yi\\n1 0.5\\n2 2.5\\n3 2.0\\n4 4.0\\n5 3.5\\n6 6.0\\n7 5.5\\nxi yi\\n0.2 8.2\\n0.4 8.4\\n0.6 8.5\\n0.8 8.6\\n1.0 8.8\\n1.2 8.7\\nMSE = SSE\\nn , RMSE =\\n√\\nSSE\\nn , NRMSE = RMSE\\n¯y\\nSr = SSE = ∑n\\ni=1 |e2\\ni | = ∑n\\ni=1 (yi − ˆy )2 = ∑n\\ni=1 (yi − a0 − a1xi )2\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 32 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nQuantification of Error of Linear Regression (cont’d)\\nMethod 2: Compare the approximate model ˆy = ax + b with the\\nNull model ˆy = ¯y (where x does not intervene)\\nWe introduce the measure R2 = 1 − SSE /TSS\\nSSE = Sum of Square Errors\\nTSS = Total Sum of Squares\\nSSE =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − ˆy )2\\nTSS =\\nn\\t∑\\ni=1\\n(yi − ¯y )2\\nclose to 1 ⇒ Perfect Model\\nclose to 0 ⇒ Null Model\\nSSE < TSS since in worst case scenario\\nthe model found is the null model\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 33 / 60\\nLinear Regression\\nExercise\\nCalculate R2 and Evaluate\\nxi yi\\n1 0.5\\n2 2.5\\n3 2.0\\n4 4.0\\n5 3.5\\n6 6.0\\n7 5.5\\nxi yi\\n0.2 8.2\\n0.4 8.4\\n0.6 8.5\\n0.8 8.6\\n1.0 8.8\\n1.2 8.7\\nR2 = 1 − SSE /TSS, SSE = ∑n\\ni=1 (yi − ˆy )2, TSS = ∑n\\ni=1 (yi − ¯y )2\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 34 / 60\\nK-Nearest Neighbors\\nK-Nearest Neighbors\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 35 / 60\\nK-Nearest Neighbors\\nKNN Algorithm\\nK-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) can be used in case of non-linear relations\\nGiven xn+1 of a new point Pn+1, find the approximate value ˆyn+1\\nAlgorithm\\n1. Choose an integer k ∈ [1, n] where n is the number of points.\\n2. Calculate the Euclidean distance √(xn+1 − xi )2 between the new\\npoint and the n points according to the abscissa\\n3. Choose the k nearest points: Pi1 , Pi2 , ..., Pik\\n4. ˆyn+1 = (yi1 + yi2 + ... + yik )\\nk\\nHow to choose k?\\nA good rule is k = √n\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 36 / 60\\nK-Nearest Neighbors\\nExercise\\nApply KNN to the approximation for the value x=4.4 and for the values\\nk=3, 4 and 5\\nxi yi\\n1 0.5\\n2 2.5\\n3 2.0\\n4 4.0\\n5 3.5\\n6 6.0\\n7 5.5\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 37 / 60\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 38 / 60\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nIntroduction\\n\\u0004 K-fold Cross Validation is a model validation technique for\\nassessing how the results of a statistical analysis will generalize to\\nan independent data set.\\n\\u0004 It is mainly used in settings where the goal is prediction, and one\\nwants to estimate how accurately a predictive model will\\nperform in practice.\\n\\u0004 In a prediction problem, a model is usually given a dataset of\\nknown data on which training is run (training dataset), and a\\ndataset of unknown data against which the model is tested\\n(validation dataset or testing set)\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 39 / 60\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nCross Validation\\n\\u0004 The goal of cross validation is to define a validation set, in order\\nto:\\nI Limit problems like overfitting\\nI Give an insight on how the model will generalize to an independent\\ndataset in a real case scenario for instance\\n\\u0004 Various cross validation techniques\\nI Test-set validation or holdout method\\nI K-fold cross-validation\\nI Leave-One-Out Cross-Validation (LOOCV)\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 40 / 60\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nTest-Set Validation / Holdout Method\\n\\u0004 Simplest kind of cross validation.\\n\\u0004 The data set is separated into two sets: the training set and the\\ntesting set.\\n\\u0004 The function ”approximator” fits a function using the training set\\nonly.\\n\\u0004 Then the function ”approximator” is asked to predict the output\\nvalues for the data in the testing set (it has never seen these output\\nvalues before).\\nAhmad Fadlallah (LU-FS) Interpolation and Extrapolation 41 / 60\\nK-fold Cross Validation\\nHow K-Fold Cross-Validation Works?\\nIn k-fold cross-validation, the original sample is randomly partitioned into\\nk equal sized subsamples.\"}],\"temperature\":0.3,\"max_tokens\":1000,\"response_format\":{\"type\":\"json_object\"}}","env":{},"headers":{"Accept":"application/json, text/plain, */*","Accept-Encoding":"gzip, compress, deflate, br","Authorization":"Bearer sk-e6c25806e5b7447e98a4ec0199a93bc0","Content-Length":"16919","Content-Type":"application/json","User-Agent":"axios/1.13.4"},"maxBodyLength":-1,"maxContentLength":-1,"method":"post","timeout":0,"transformRequest":[null],"transformResponse":[null],"transitional":{"clarifyTimeoutError":false,"forcedJSONParsing":true,"silentJSONParsing":true},"url":"https://api.deepseek.com/v1/chat/completions","xsrfCookieName":"XSRF-TOKEN","xsrfHeaderName":"X-XSRF-TOKEN"},"isAxiosError":true,"level":"error","message":"DeepSeek API error: Request failed with status code 402","name":"AxiosError","request":{"_closed":true,"_contentLength":16919,"_defaultKeepAlive":true,"_ended":true,